The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta, Jan. 5: Representatives of va-rious chambers of commerce led by Assocham president Swati Piramal will meet chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee tomorrow.     
	Assocham, which is organising a summit to sell Bengal as an investment destination, feels the state must play a facilitator in land acquisition for industrial use. Negotiations should take place between buyers and sellers (with the government playing facilitator), secretary-general D.S. Rawat said. The chamber will also unveil tomorrow a study on Bengals potential to attract investment.        
	Calcutta: A singer from Bangladesh, Mohammed Mujibar Rahaman, was arrested in South 24-Parganas Joyna-gar on Monday because he had no valid passport. Mujibar told the police that the Bangladesh Rifles had taken away his passport when he was crossing over. The police said he was primarily a folk singer and had performed at several soirees in Calcutta and the two 24-Parganas.        
	Calcutta: Jyoti Basus condition was said to be stable on Tuesday. However, he is still in the intensive care unit.         
	Suri: The principal of a Suri college has shut it down indefinitely after the non-teaching staff held him hostage for over seven hours de- manding that a clerk be recruited from among them. The Vidyasagar College principal called police and locked its gates in their presence.
                                                                                                                                                      
